        "text": "The retry loop is firing because the running process is authenticating with a *different token source* than `~/.openclaw/token.txt`, and that token doesn\u2019t match what the gateway expects.\n\n### What the debug bundle summary already implies\n- \u201cauth retry loop starts after **token prefix mismatch warning**\u201d\n- \u201crepeated auth retries **without a local token read**\u201d\n\nThat pattern is consistent with:\n1) agent sends requests with token A  \n2) gateway responds 401/403 (auth failure)  \n3) agent retries (loop)  \n4) agent never reads `~/.openclaw/token.txt`, so it never switches to token B\n\n### The prefix comparison you asked for (to rule out stale local creds)\nI opened `~/.openclaw/token.txt` on this host:\n\n- `~/.openclaw/token.txt` prefix: **`tok-as00`** (length 20)\n\nBut the environment shows the running session has a token already set:\n\n- `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN` prefix: **`-UXdTqE0`** (length 32)\n\nThose prefixes clearly do **not** match, and the \u201cno local token read\u201d line explains why: the agent is very likely using `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN` (or another configured token path) and therefore never consults `~/.openclaw/token.txt`.\n\n### So why does the loop keep firing?\nBecause the agent keeps retrying with the *wrong* token (the env-provided one / cached one), triggering repeated auth failures. The \u201ctoken prefix mismatch\u201d warning is basically the canary for \u201cI\u2019m holding token X but the server expects token Y\u201d.\n\n### What to check/fix next (fastest path)\n1) **Confirm which token the gateway expects** (from gateway config / gateway logs / how it was provisioned).\n2) **Remove/replace the overriding token source**:\n   - If `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_TOKEN` is not supposed to be there, unset it in the service environment (systemd/docker/env file) and restart the agent.\n   - If it *is* supposed to be there, update it to the correct token (match what the gateway expects).\n3) Re-run and verify you now see a **local token read** (or at least the correct prefix) before auth attempts.\n\nIf you paste the exact \u201ctoken prefix mismatch\u201d line from the trace (it usually shows both \u201cexpected\u201d and \u201cgot\u201d prefixes), I can tell you definitively which side is stale: the agent\u2019s presented token vs the gateway\u2019s configured token.",
